                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a4">
                                    <desc type="CalendaricNote"/>
                                    <locus target="#142r">f. 142r </locus>
                                    <quote xml:lang="gez">ዘአርዓያ፡ ዘሳቤላ፡ ፱ፀሐይ፡ ወ፩ዘመን፡ ፯፻ወ፸ወ፰። ወታሰዓይሰ፡ ዘመን፡ ዓመታቲሁ። ፯፻ወ፸ወ፯። ዘሳቤላ፡ ቀመር፡ ፰፻ወ፯፻ወ፩ለ፩፡ ዘመን፡ ፰፻፡ ዓመት። ዝዕዝራ፡ ቀመር። ፵ወ፱ወ፩ቀመር፡ ፻ወ፵ወ፫ዓመት። ዘሄኖክ፡ ቀመር፡ ፲ለ፩ዘመን፡ ፯፻ዓመት። ለእግዚአቭሔር፡ ዕለታቲሁ፡ ፯ወበኀቤነሰ፡ ዕለታት። ፪፻፼ወ፭፼ወ፹፻።</quote>
                                    <quote xml:lang="en"/>
                                    <p>The note records the number of cycles and years per cycle according to the computation systems of Sibyl, Ezra and Enoch.</p>
                                    <listBibl type="text">
                                        <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/FVDGF5SX"
                                    type="journalArticle">
                                 <title level="a">Die Weisheit der Sibylle</title>
                                 <title level="j">Wiener Zeitschrift für die Kunde des Morgenlandes</title>
                                 <author>
                                    <forename>Joel</forename>
                                    <surname>Schleifer</surname>
                                 </author>
                                 <date>1910</date>
                                 <biblScope unit="volume">24</biblScope>
                                 <biblScope unit="page">33-50</biblScope>
                                 <citedRange unit="page">3a-3b</citedRange>
                              </bibl>
                                    </listBibl>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a5">
                                    <desc>List of canonical books</desc>
                                    <locus target="#142">f. 142 </locus>
                                    <quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <quote xml:lang="en"/>
                                    <p>The note lists the books of the Old and the New Testament according to the Ethiopian canon. The total number of books is also provided.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a6">
                                    <desc type="CalendaricNote"/>
                                    <locus target="#142">f. 142 </locus>
                                    <quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <quote xml:lang="en">"The days since Adam until the end of the world (are) 2.556.750; one cycle (has) 194.180 days; (the number of) cycles of Adam (is) 13, each cycle (has) 532 years. The cycles of the Jubilees (are) 142 seven-year-cycles, each cycle (has) 42 years".</quote>
                                    <p>The note records the number of days since Adam until the end of the world, the number of days and years per cycle according to the computation system of Adam.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a7">
                                    <desc type="ScribalNoteCompleting"/>
                                    <locus target="#142">f. 142 </locus>
                                    <quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                                    <quote xml:lang="en">"(The book of) Ezra (and) Sibyl is finished. Who allowed me to finish this book with my hands, the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit, shall be glorified now and ever, forever and ever. Amen. Who wrote it is me, Tābor, the sinner; remind of me".</quote>
                                    <p>The note follows <ref target="#ms_i5"/>. It mentions <persName ref="https://www.betamasaheft.uni-hamburg.de/PRS10768Tabor"/> as the scribe.</p>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="a8">
                                    <desc type="Poem"/>
                                    <locus target="#143">f. 143 </locus>
                                    <p>Rhymed poem in honor of <persName ref="https://www.betamasaheft.uni-hamburg.de/PRS6819Mary"/>, incomplete.</p>
                                </item>
                            </list>
